{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"709713d4-9ec7-453d-8592-480be029a972","content":"Here's what I found:\n\n**`my_app/views.py:3`** — `datetime.now()` is called directly, making it hard to mock in tests.\n\n```python\nnow = datetime.now()\n```\n\n### Recommendation\n\nInject the clock dependency so tests can control time. For example, use Django's `django.utils.timezone.now` (which is easier to patch) or inject a callable:\n\n```python\nfrom django.utils import timezone\n\ndef index(request, now=timezone.now):\n    current_time = now()\n    return render(request, 'index.html', {'time': current_time})\n```\n\nThis way tests can simply pass a lambda: `index(request, now=lambda: datetime(2026, 1, 1))`.\n\n**Summary:** Only 1 file with 1 untestable static call found. The project is small — just the single `datetime.now()` in `views.py`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"10c590e0-17a8-4f3d-a09f-31587c7d1652","outputTokens":217,"requestId":"0C0D:31F00F:64D523A:6E2D839:69F01FEA"},"id":"5d27c8e4-a349-4330-9f96-6ff4d08f2ba4","timestamp":"2026-04-28T02:48:17.782Z","parentId":"04662a91-5730-41bf-a784-75923c0e7b45"}
